1 ENGR OSSED SENATE
CONCURRENT
2 RESOLUTION NO. 22 By: Nice of the Senate
3 and
4 Hefner of the House
5
6 A Concurrent Resolution recognizing the impact of
light pollution on bird mortality; and encouraging
7 Oklahoma businesses, state agencies, organizations,
and residents to turn off any exterior lighting
8 during the high migration intensity months of April,
May, September and October.
9
10
11 WHEREAS, the State of Oklahoma and the Oklahoma Animal Coalition
12 aim to provide birds safe passage during migration periods by
13 reducing light pollution, as well as building and glass collisions,
14 through the Lights Out Oklahoma campaign; and
15 WHEREAS, birds help with the control of pests, carrion
16 regulation, pollination, and seed dispersal while adding beauty and
17 connecting people to nature and the outdoors; and
18 WHEREAS, birdwatching is an economic driver in the State of
19 Oklahoma and is a fun, relaxing, multigenerational, educational and
20 wellness activity for all; and
21 WHEREAS, a wide diversity of birds in Oklahoma indicates a
22 healthy environment; and
23
24
ENGR. S. C. R. NO. 22 Page 1

1 WHEREAS, Oklahoma is part of the central flyway through which
2 approximately 400 different species of birds migrate during the
3 spring and fall; and
4 WHEREAS, the Oklahoma state bird, the scissor-tailed flycatcher,
5 is one of the many species of birds that migrate to our state to
6 nest and rear their young; and
7 WHEREAS, most birds migrate at night, navigate by using the
8 stars and moon, and can become disoriented by bright artificial
9 light and sky glow, resulting in exhaustion and deadly collisions
10 with buildings, glass, power lines, and vehicles; and
11 WHEREAS, collisions with buildings is one of the top causes of
12 mortality of birds in the United States; and
13 WHEREAS, the Lights Out Oklahoma program strategy is aimed to
14 persuade building owners and managers and homeowners to turn off
15 exterior lighting on all buildings at night during the high
16 migration intensity months of April, May, September and October; and
17 WHEREAS, these measures save energy and money and protect birds
18 migrating to nesting grounds in the spring and wintering grounds in
19 the fall; and
20 WHEREAS, Oklahoma joins the international community and states
21 including Texas, Colorado, Kansas, Missouri and Florida in
22 sponsoring Lights Out projects to protect birds during migration.
23
24
ENGR. S. C. R. NO. 22 Page 2

1 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE 2ND SESSION
2 OF THE 60TH OKLAHOMA LEGISLATURE, THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
3 CONCURRING THEREIN:
4 THAT the Oklahoma State Legislature supports reducing bird
5 mortality in the areas and encourages Oklahoma businesses, state
6 agencies, organizations, and residents to turn off any exterior
7 lighting during the high migration intensity months of April, May,
8 September and October.
9 Adopted by the Senate the 22nd day of April, 2026.
